_data.description:
Admission to the Nancy & David Wolf Holocaust & Humanity Center is free for general public in January.
Supported by the Anita & Hank Schneider Family Holocaust Remembrance Month initiative.


The Nancy & David Wolf Holocaust & Humanity Center exists to ensure the lessons of the Holocaust inspire action today. HHC educates about the Holocaust, remembers its victims and acts on its lessons. Through innovative programs and partnerships, HHC challenges injustice, inhumanity, and prejudice, and fosters understanding, inclusion, and engaged citizenship. HHC impacts more than 180,000 individuals each year.


After visiting Auschwitz. Not Long Ago. Not Far Away. (October 18, 2025 - April 12, 2026), take the next step on your journey by exploring stories of survival and resilience right here in Cincinnati. The Nancy & David Wolf Holocaust & Humanity Center is the only Holocaust museum in the United States with a direct, authentic connection to its site — located inside historic Union Terminal, where Holocaust survivors once arrived to rebuild their lives. Be inspired by local stories of courage, loss, and hope, and discover how their legacies continue to shape our community today. Through powerful exhibits and hands-on experiences, you’ll learn how to activate your own character strengths and become an upstander in your own life. *When you purchase admission to Auschwitz. Not Long Ago. Not Far Away., receive discounted Holocaust & Humanity Center admission — just $7.50 for adults.

_data.description:
This book tells a story to shake the conscience of the world. It is the catalogue of the first-ever traveling exhibition about the Auschwitz concentration camp, where 1.1 million people―mostly Jews, but also non-Jewish Poles, Roma, and others―lost their lives. More than 280 objects and images from the exhibition are illustrated herein. Drawn from the Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum and other collections around the world, they range from the intimate (such as victims’ family snapshots and personal belongings) to the immense (an actual surviving barrack from the Auschwitz III–Monowitz satellite camp); all are eloquent in their testimony. An authoritative yet accessible text weaves the stories behind these artifacts into an encompassing history of Auschwitz―from a Polish town at the crossroads of Europe, to the dark center of the Holocaust, to a powerful site of remembrance. Auschwitz: Not long ago. Not far away. is an essential volume for everyone who is interested in history and its lessons.

Book Collection Instructions: Auschwitz: Not Long Ago. Not Far Away. Exhibition Book must be collected from the Museum Store during regular hours of operation through the run of the Auschwitz: Not Long Ago. Not Far Away. exhibit (October 18, 2025 - April 12, 2026).
_data.name: Auschwitz: Not Long Ago. Not Far Away. Exhibition Book
_data.subtitle: by Luis Ferreiro, Miriam Greenbaum, Robert Jan van Pelt (Editor)

_data.description:
Part historic journey and part forensic adventure, Mummies: Secrets of the Pharaohs follows researchers and explorers as they piece together the archeological and genetic clues of Egyptian mummies. These relics of the past create a window into the fascinating and mysterious world of the pharaohs. In addition to increasing our understanding of the culture, religion, medicine, and daily life of the Egyptians thousands of years ago, scientists today are reconstructing mummy DNA to gain insight into modern human genetics and to advance medical treatments. To unwrap the secrets of the pharaohs is to perhaps glimpse the future of our own civilization.
No food or drink is permitted. Runtime: 50 minutes

Upcoming programs:
  • December 6: Asian Street Food Favorites: Dumplings, Fried Rice, and Boba 
    Get ready to roll up your sleeves and explore the flavors and techniques behind some of Asia’s favorite street foods! In this hands-on class, you will learn how to fold and boil dumplings to perfection and create perfectly seasoned fried rice. Finish with a sweet treat as you mix your own bubble tea (boba) and learn about its origins in Taiwan. Along the way, we’ll share the cultural stories, techniques, and culinary science that make these dishes so special.

    Dive into the techniques behind classic Indian dishes in this hands-on class! You’ll learn how to make a flavorful curry using tadka, the traditional method of tempering spices to bring out their aroma and depth. You’ll also prepare raita and roll and cook your own roti, gaining skills that you can use to recreate these dishes at home.
    • Vegetarian
    • Allergens: Dairy, Flour, Coconut Milk

  • February 7: Big Flavors, Southern Style: Gumbo & Cornbread
    Get hands-on with a Southern classic! Learn how to make a rich, flavorful gumbo by starting with a holy trinity of onions, bell peppers, and celery, building a deep robust roux, and layering spices for depth. Then, bake your own cornbread to enjoy alongside it. By the end of class, you’ll be ready to share these comforting dishes with family and friends.

_data.description:
Build Your Own Power Bowl: Food as Medicine Series Powered by the Osher Center for Integrative Health at UC

Join us for a nourishing, hands-on cooking class where participants will build vibrant power bowls featuring quinoa, marinated tempeh, and a rainbow of fresh, colorful vegetables. After we cook and enjoy our meal, Dr. Barbara Walker will lead an engaging presentation on the connection between what we eat and how we feel, exploring food, mood, and gut health. A delicious and uplifting experience for both body and mind!
Allergens: Sesame, Soy

Dr. Barbara Walker, an Integrative Health and Performance Psychologist at the University of Cincinnati College of Medicine, specializes in optimizing performance in sport, career, health, and recovery from illness or injury. She integrates biofeedback, mind-body techniques, lifestyle medicine, and high-performance strategies to foster resilience and self-regulation. As Director of the Nature as Medicine program through the Osher Center for Integrative Health and a certified forest immersion guide, she promotes the science-backed health benefits of time in nature. She teaches courses in Sport and Positive Psychology, Nature-Based Therapies, and Mind-Body Medicine, and has a strong passion for teaching the vital connection between food and mood. A former competitive endurance athlete, she now enjoys cycling, hiking, yoga, gardening, and outdoor time with family and friends.
